<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Trade, UIC Reports 11 Trillion </F>
Surplus in 1993"] 
  [Text] Rome, 25 Feb (ANSA) -- Italy posted a 10.979 
trillion lire trade-related exchange surplus in 1993, after 
registering a 15.866 trillion deficit in 1992, reported the 
Italian Exchange Office, UIC. In the month of December alone, 
Italy's surplus reached 2.421 trillion lire, exchange 
authorities added. 
  The figures are based on that office's records of all 
trade-related currency exchange operations exceeding 20 million 
lire in value. They do not correspond exactly to trade balance 
figures reported by the National Institute of Statistics Istat, 
which records goods and services crossing the border. 
  According to UIC's records, Italy's trade revenues last 
year totaled 219.413 trillion lire, as against payments of 
208.434 trillion. In the month of December, the outgoing total 
was 21.447 trillion (15.3 percent) while the incoming was 19.026 
trillion lire (1.9 percent). 
  Machinery and transport were the sectors showing greatest 
improvement over last year. Exchange balances with Germany and 
the United States improved most in 1993. 
  The following table outlines Italy's trade balance with 
other 
European and non-EU countries, based on UIC's exchange records. 


